I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to critically view them.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could rush into things without having to question where they came from, because back then it wasn't so easy to figure that out anyway.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency toward nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the show together.
That was completely different from today's streaming, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like it, and posts social media messages with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Unconsciously, we long for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," which contain so many one-liners that would be memes today.
We all knew these catchphrases and assumed that most people already understood them.
Today, you can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads virally in massive numbers.
There is far too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Will we ever get out of this saturation?
We are trapped in a cycle of constantly discovering new content, only to realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we have to hold on to our nostalgia while at the same time accepting that the people who created the works we liked can also have major flaws.
We engage in parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's feet along the way.
Since we have lost our collective consciousness regarding media, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall down.
We are in a phase of transition and I am curious where it will ultimately lead.
